Beautiful rougelike with tight combat, what's not to like. Mechanics are simple, yet deep. There are only 3 buttons: left right and shoot, which doubles as a jump button. You readoad when hitting the floor or jumping on an enemy that is of the correct coloring (there are fully colored enemies you can't jump on). It is very fast paced, and very minimal to maximize the visual clarity of the game. TL;DR, a fast paced rougelike with tight controls and fluitidy to create a beautiful experience.

Downwell is an incredible game. Its simplistic controls do wonders for gameplay and everything is beautiful to look at. Its the kind of game that anyone can play and enjoy, captivating the player. The price may seem a little high, but it truly is worth every penny. Easily one of the best games I have ever played on a mobile device.

An incredibly meticulous and well-made phone game. Downwell will have you playing for hours in your own home because it's that fun. It's addicting, but it achieves this without the use of predatory, anti-consumer features like wait times, loss-aversion. This game is hard, be warned, and action-packed. A lot of phone gamers may not be looking for a twitchy game like Downwell, and if that's the case, turn back. However, if fast-paced gameplay appeals to you, it's absolutely worth the $3.

A modern arcade classic. If you're into challenging games with a lot of replayability (just like games of the 80s) then this is for you. It's a true computer game. Most games aren't really games (they're interactive stories) but this is a real game. Honestly great work whoever made it

Well, I see my other review has been removed, so let me restate again what happened in the past, they took the original game out of the store and replaced it with the same "new" version, and google appearantly gave everyone a week to reclaim their game, of course i never figured it out for weeks after it had been done (who tells us these things? (not google nor the developers) but after reaching out to them they did replace the game they took from my account with the new version (which was identical to the original version mind you). The developer KNOWS who all bought the game, but did they reach out to everyone and explain what was happening? NO.. did google? NO.. the play store has some really screwed up policies it seems (as if we all didn't already know that). When a developer sells a game and then takes it from the end user, it shouldn't be considered a "sale" at all, but rather a "theft by deception with unequal protection from the google play store" I still find myself wondering how many people they robbed in those few days. Would be one thing if they notified the person that purchased the game but they don't, I hope next time they do. I for my part no longer do business with anyone that has removed and readded a game (an identical game) to the play store.
